Just noticed that calling OpenFile on a container with FileMode.Open is throwing an AccessDenied exception. After checking the MonoGame code:
`folder.CreateFileAsync(filePath, CreationCollisionOption.OpenIfExists).AsTask().GetAwaiter().GetResult().OpenAsync(FileAccessMode.ReadWrite).AsTask().GetAwaiter().GetResult().AsStream();
var f = folder.CreateFileAsync(filePath, CreationCollisionOption.OpenIfExists).AsTask().GetAwaiter().GetResult();
                return f.OpenAsync(FileAccessMode.ReadWrite).AsTask().GetAwaiter().GetResult().AsStream();
`

I found that this code is causing the problem as the first line is gaining access to the file (basically doing what the next two lines do) and when the next 2 lines come in there is an access denied due to file being already in use by the first line.

When i am creating sound effect like this:

```
 using (System.IO.Stream stream = TitleContainer.OpenStream(@"Content\" + songName))
                        {
                            using (var effect = SoundEffect.FromStream(stream))
                            {
                                bgmDuration = effect.Duration.TotalMilliseconds;
                                bgm = effect.CreateInstance();
                            }
                        }
```

And disposing it like this: 

```
if (bgm != null)
                        {
                            if (!bgm.IsDisposed)
                            {
                                bgm.Stop();
                                while (bgm.State != SoundState.Stopped)
                                {
                                    Task.WaitAny(Task.Delay(100));
                                }
                                bgm.Dispose();
                            }
                            bgm = null;
                        }

```

Then memory leaks.

